# csv

CSV done right. @text/cut and @text/awk split on a literal delimiter, so they
mangle a quoted field that *contains* a comma — Miller (`mlr`) parses real CSV by
header name instead. `columns` projects fields by name; `filter` keeps matching
rows; `tojson` converts; `sort` orders by a column. Every recipe assumes a header
row (`--csv` = named fields).

| Recipe | Verb | Does |
|--------|------|------|
| `columns` | `cut -f` | keep only the named columns |
| `filter` | `filter` | keep rows where an expression is true |
| `tojson` | `--ojson cat` | convert CSV to JSON records |
| `sort` | `sort -f/-nf` | order rows by a column (lexical or numeric) |

Fields are referenced by `$name` in expressions: `filter '$age > 30'`,
`put '$full = $first . " " . $last'`. Miller chains verbs with `then`
(`mlr --csv cut -f a,b then sort -nr a file`), the structured-data analogue of a
shell pipe. `--c2j` is shorthand for CSV-in/JSON-out; `--c2p` gives pretty
aligned output (like @text/format). For YAML/JSON config files instead of
tabular data, see @search/yq and @search/jq.

```just
# keep only the named columns (comma-separated), header-aware (default)
columns fields file:
  mlr --csv cut -f {{quote(fields)}} {{quote(file)}}

# keep rows where an expression is true (e.g. '$age > 30')
filter expr file:
  mlr --csv filter {{quote(expr)}} {{quote(file)}}

# convert CSV to JSON records
tojson file:
  mlr --c2j cat {{quote(file)}}

# sort by a column; numeric="-nf" for numeric, default lexical "-f"
sort field flag="-f" file:
  mlr --csv sort {{flag}} {{quote(field)}} {{quote(file)}}
```
